column55: I was wondering what would be a significant enough change to log, and I think my logging became more strict after I talked with colleagues who were also participating in the study. Generally though, I kept going about my normal life.
column56: Transitional states were hard to log, often because I would either forget about it, or do it during the actual transitional state which meant it was over by the time I'd finished logging. Logging during stressful or busy moments (i.e. catching a train, etc.) which require a lot of bandwidth was also hard.
column57: It was not clear why I would still have to log indoor lighting conditions when I stated I was fully outside. Instructions generally were pretty vague as to what should be considered a significant enough change in state given the sampling rate of the device. Also, I wonder why the event button on the ActLumus device was not used to keep precise tracking of state changes, which has less participant burden that filling in a survey.

column56: I found it challenging to accurately log light exposure when moving between rooms (at home) - especially because the illumination always seems to be very uniform in my home. I also believe my self-reported screen time, especially smartphone use, was likely underestimated.
column57: Overall, I think the logging method will create a very rich dataset, the instructions were very clear, and I had a positive experience!    I've noticed the options for the outdoor setting focus exclusively on daylight conditions (direct sunlight or shade). It might be helpful to include an option for outdoors during nighttime. Of course, this is a minor point, since it's easy to access photoperiod retrospectively.    Also, while the level of detail is great for capturing rich data, I'm not sure how sustainable this protocol would be if one needs to collect data for more than a few days in a row - probably changes in the logging format would have to be made.

column57: Some of the instructions were a little unclear, or could be helped by using logic - eg sometimes I would select that I was outdoors only, but was still asked about electric lighting. The electric lighting options included "complete darkness" but often I am indoors with natural light, and my electric lights were off, but I was not in "complete darkness" - switched off may be more accurate.     For the question about having control over lighting, I was a bit confused about how to answer this in relation to outdoor lighting - I selected NA but was not confident this was correct. I wondered if it was meaning to ask "could you have control" over the lighting, or HAVE you (eg made a decision to be in the setting you are).      Some of the tenses could also be clarified - you are answering questions about the state / environment which WILL happen after logging (eg when going to sleep I would select complete darkness, but was not actually in complete darkness at the time of completing the log).
